This article discusses the United States' relationship with Central and South America in terms of economic growth and trade partnerships. The article highlights the rapid pace of growth in the region, with a GDP projected to rise from $3.6 trillion to $4.8 trillion by 2015. The United States aims to double its exports by the end of 2014, and trade agreements with Central and South American countries already cover 7 countries and $471 billion in total goods trade. The article also provides specific information about Brazil, Chile, and El Salvador, highlighting their economic growth, trade relationships with the United States, and foreign direct investment figures.